Explanation:
- I scanned routers.go for explicit router registration calls (router.GET, router.POST, router.PUT, router.DELETE) and extracted each literal path string provided as the first argument.
- Gin path parameters written as :name were converted to the required {name} form in the output (for example ":slug" -> "{slug}", ":id" -> "{id}").
- Each handler references a named function defined later in the same file (ArticleCreate, ArticleUpdate, ArticleDelete, ArticleFavorite, ArticleUnfavorite, ArticleCommentCreate, ArticleCommentDelete, ArticleList, ArticleRetrieve, ArticleCommentList, TagList), so handler_is_defined_in_file is true and handler is the function name. There are no anonymous handlers in this file.
- All paths are literal strings in this source file (is_literal = true). None are derived via a framework naming convention (is_derived_from_framework_convention = false).
- I marked is_prefix = false for all entries because the strings provided are exact route patterns relative to the router group (not a wildcard prefix registration).
- These routes implement the RESTful articles/tags API (is_rest = true) and are normal application endpoints (is_testing = false).
- I did not include functions that are not directly registered with router methods (for example ArticleFeed is not directly registered; it is called internally by ArticleRetrieve when the slug equals "feed"), nor did I include any routes not literally present in this file.

path.description: The HTTP request path, which must begin with a forward slash (/) and have path parameters wrapped in curly braces ({}). Set this to null if it cannot be determined.

handler.description: The function, class, class method, or object that handles the HTTP request. Use exactly "anonymous" to denote an anonymous implementation.
handler.title: Handler

handler_in_same_file.description: Whether the handler's implementation is present in the same source code file, rather than being imported.
handler_in_same_file.title: Handler In Same File

path_is_prefix.description: Whether the path string is a prefix rather than a full path.
path_is_prefix.title: Path Is Prefix

path_from_string_literal.title: Path From String Literal

path_from_naming_convention.description: Whether the path string is derived from a naming convention supported by the framework.
path_from_naming_convention.title: Path From Naming Convention
